" {TEXT -1 2 "  " }{TEXT 279 58 "What's the famous formula we get when
 we solve p3=0 for x?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 169 "  See if MAPLE knows a general formula for solving ge
neral cubic polynomials, i.e. is there a 3rd order formula comparable \+
to the quadratic formula?  If so, exhibit it. " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 297 2 "  " }}}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 280 111 "W
hy do you think high school students are never asked to remember the g
eneral formula for the roots of a cubic?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
12 "I don't know" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 113 "4.  Solving Equation
s in One Variable.   There are two different commands to direct Maple \+
to solve an equation:  " }{TEXT 285 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 5 " and " }
{TEXT 286 7 "fsolve." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "They have differe
nt purposes.  The " }{TEXT 287 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 63 " command attemp
ts to find exact solutions.  If the expression  " }{TEXT 289 1 "f" }
{TEXT -1 116 "  is defined in terms of only one variable, there are se
veral different ways to direct Maple to solve the equation  " }{TEXT 
290 5 "f  = " }{TEXT 291 4 "0.  " }{TEXT -1 54 "The following all caus
e Maple to solve the equation   " }{TEXT 292 5 "f  = " }{TEXT 293 2 "0
." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 16 "    \+
   solve(f);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f,x);" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f=0);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 20 "       solve(f=0,x);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 349 "Maple makes an assumption that if the co
efficients of a polynomial are all given exactly (as integers or ratio
nal numbers [ratios of integer]), then you are only interested in find
ing exact solutions.  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra doesn't guara
ntee that the solutions of  a polynomial can be found exactly, only th
e polynomial has solutions.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 78 "You can force Maple to report additional \+
(approximate) solutions by using the " }{TEXT 288 6 "fsolve" }{TEXT 
-1 45 " command.  (What does the \"f\" stand for?)  In" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "addition, to forcing Maple to report approximate so
lutions, you can specify a field extension (typically real or complex)
 and require Maple to look for solutions which fit in that field exten
sion.  Also, one can specify a range of x values and force" }{TEXT 
296 7 " fsolve" }{TEXT -1 75 " to only look for solutions in that spec
ified range.  For example, compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 11 "f:=4*x-x^3;" }}{PARA 11 "" 
1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%\"fG,&*&\"\"%\"\"\"%\"xGF(F(*$)F)\"\"$F(!\"\"" }
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "fsolve(4*x-x^3);" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6%$!+++++?!\"*$\"\"!F'$\"+++++?F%" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 23 "fsolve(4*x-x^3,x=1..4);" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#$\"+++++?!\"*" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "For each of the polynomials " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p[1]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"\"\"" }{TEXT -1 9 " through " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p[14]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"#9" }{TEXT -1 19 ", do the followin
g:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "     a.   solve for all exact roots
 whereever possible, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 59 "     b.   find a
ll approximate roots to 10 decimal places, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 43 "     c.  factor each into linear factors.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
