{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "solve(p12,x);" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "solve(p13,x);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "solve(p14,x);" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
56 "5.  Solving Systems of Equations in Several Variables.  " }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 49 "When we \+
have an equation in two variables, e.g.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x -2*y = \+
5" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"yGF'!\"\"\"\"&" }{TEXT -1 
147 "  we often associate with it a graph, the set of points (x,y) in \+
the two-dimensional plane which satisfy the equation.  For a linear eq
uation like " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x-2*y = 5" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F
'*&\"\"#F'%\"yGF'!\"\"\"\"&" }{TEXT -1 89 " the graph is a straight li
ne.  For more a complicated equation in two variables, e.g.,  " }
{XPPEDIT 19 1 "2*x^3 -3*x + y^2 = x*y" "6#/,(*&\"\"#\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"$
F'F'*&F*F'F)F'!\"\"*$%\"yGF&F'*&F)F'F.F'" }{TEXT -1 45 "  the graph be
comes a more complicated curve." }}{PARA 8 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 25 "Error,
 unexpected number\n" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 282 "When we have two equations in two variables, we think
 of the solution set of this system of equations as being the set of p
oints (x,y) which satisfy both equations simultaneously.  In terms of \+
their graphs, the solution set is the set of points where the graphs i
ntersect (cross).  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 622 "When we have two linear equations in two variables, si
nce their graphs are straight lines, then two straight lines, if they \+
cross, will cross in exactly one place.  Hence, the solution set of th
e system of equations will be exactly one point (x,y).  If we have two
 equations which are more complicated, then the number of intersection
 points (crossing points) of their graphs can vary.  For example, if t
he graph of one equation is a circle and the graph of the other equati
on is a straight line, then, if their graphs cross, then number of sol
utions (intersection points) of the system of equations could be 1 or \+
2.  Etc." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
128 "We can instruct Maple to find solutions of systems of equations u
sing the solve or fsolve commands.  The syntax for doing so is:" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 30 "     solv
e( \{eq1,eq2\}, \{x,y\});" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 85 "where eq1 and eq2 are equations in the variables \+
x and y.  This is illustrated below." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" 
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 42 "solve(\{ x + 2*y = 5, 2*x-
3*y = -1\},\{x,y\});" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 22 "We could have defined " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 40 "eq1 := x + 2*y = 5;\neq2 := 2*x-3*y = -1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#>%$eq1G/,&%\"xG\"\"\"*&\"\"#F(%\"yGF(F(\"\"&" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%$eq2G/,&*&\"\"#\"\"\"%\"xGF)F)*&\"\"$F)%\"
yGF)!\"\"F." }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 26 "and then given the command" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
25 "solve( \{eq1,eq2\}, \{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<
$/%\"yG#\"#6\"\"(/%\"xG#\"#8F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 55 "and achieved the same result.  Remember t
he solution  (" }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "13/7" "6#*&\"#8\"\"\"\"\"(!\"\"" }
{TEXT -1 2 ", " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "11/7" "6#*&\"#6\"\"\"\"\"(!\"\"" }
{TEXT -1 127 ") represents a point in the two-dimensional plane (why t
wo-dimensional?) where the graphs of the equations intersect (cross). \+
 " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 63 "Find
 the solutions, if they exist, for the following equations " }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "a.  " }{XPPEDIT 
